00:00:15,496 --> 00:00:19,018
No offense, love the song. Carry on. Go.

4
00:00:25,848 --> 00:00:27,553
And wuss patrol, halt.

5
00:00:28,689 --> 00:00:30,539
I've never known such pain.

6
00:00:30,661 --> 00:00:32,234
We are so not walking around Europe

7
00:00:32,299 --> 00:00:33,964
with those annoying things on our backs.

8
00:00:34,061 --> 00:00:35,480
But we're backpacking through Europe.

9
00:00:35,546 --> 00:00:37,169
How're we gonna do this without backpacks?

10
00:00:37,246 --> 00:00:38,829
But all the time we've talked about backpacking,

11
00:00:38,870 --> 00:00:40,728
I never actually pictured us with backpacks.

12
00:00:40,805 --> 00:00:41,853
What were you picturing?

13
00:00:42,244 --> 00:00:44,972
Spry, accommodating European men

14
00:00:45,024 --> 00:00:47,574
with neat mustaches trailing after us, carrying our luggage,

15
00:00:47,676 --> 00:00:51,035
hailing taxi cabs, constantly reminding us how beautiful we are.

16
00:00:51,091 --> 00:00:53,758
No, it's just the two of us humping our backpacks around.

17
00:00:53,815 --> 00:00:57,424
Well, at least my new walking shoes are all broken in.

18
00:00:57,543 --> 00:00:59,923
If you count broken skin, broken toes.

19
00:00:59,995 --> 00:01:01,807
- Don't do that. 
- Don't do what?

20
00:01:01,879 --> 00:01:03,486
Don't take your shoes off. This is a restaurant.

21
00:01:03,593 --> 00:01:05,648
I don't see a "No shirt, no shoes, no service" sign.

22
00:01:05,694 --> 00:01:06,958
It's right here, don't do that.

23
00:01:07,036 --> 00:01:08,151
We're in pain, Luke.

24
00:01:08,207 --> 00:01:11,239
But it's great that you guys are bearing it so nobly. And can you move these?

25
00:01:11,311 --> 00:01:12,324
Can? No.

26
00:01:12,390 --> 00:01:13,743
Would if we could? Debatable.

27
00:01:15,878 --> 00:01:18,069
- Look at that. 
- Spry and accommodating.

28
00:01:18,157 --> 00:01:20,572
Hey, would you grow a mustache and follow us around Europe?

29
00:01:20,675 --> 00:01:22,949
- Sorry, got travel plans of my own. 
- Really?

30
00:01:23,015 --> 00:01:24,751
Yup, I'm closing down the diner for a couple of weeks

31
00:01:24,819 --> 00:01:26,329
and taking Nicole on a little trip.

32
00:01:26,406 --> 00:01:27,072
Fun.

33
00:01:27,152 --> 00:01:30,557
We're driving through Western Canada and then taking a cruise up to Alaska.

34
00:01:30,640 --> 00:01:32,288
- A cruise? 
- Intimate.

35
00:01:32,360 --> 00:01:32,959
I guess.

36
00:01:33,585 --> 00:01:35,431
- Is it? 
- The Love Boat.

37
00:01:35,478 --> 00:01:35,950
What?

38
00:01:36,020 --> 00:01:38,489
A cruise is a good spot to get down on one knee.

39
00:01:38,561 --> 00:01:40,651
And do my ventriloquist act?

40
00:01:40,707 --> 00:01:43,527
- And propose. 
- I have no plans to propose.

41
00:01:43,615 --> 00:01:46,835
You don't now, but after you've had dinner at Captain Stubing's table

42
00:01:46,933 --> 00:01:49,424
and Isaac's served you up a couple of mojitos.

43
00:01:49,688 --> 00:01:51,624
Romantic cruises say commitment, my friend.

44
00:01:51,711 --> 00:01:54,438
I am not committing and I am not proposing, so drop it.

45
00:01:54,464 --> 00:01:56,506
- Okay, it's dropped. 
- Really drop it.

46
00:01:56,608 --> 00:01:59,267
- Did I not just say it's dropped? 
- Heard it with my own ears.

47
00:01:59,335 --> 00:02:00,000
Thank you.

48
00:02:00,435 --> 00:02:02,371
The Love Boat.

49
00:02:03,087 --> 00:02:04,715
If you'd get a radio in here, I wouldn't have to do that.

50
00:02:04,919 --> 00:02:07,546
Okay, so your graduation is Wednesday at four, correct?

51
00:02:07,674 --> 00:02:09,590
You know, you really don't have to go to it, Luke.

52
00:02:09,671 --> 00:02:12,289
I want to. I feel like I've been through this whole Chilton thing with you.

53
00:02:12,370 --> 00:02:13,844
Okay, good, I want you there.

54
00:02:13,942 --> 00:02:14,936
Good. So what do you want?

55
00:02:15,622 --> 00:02:17,398
- Are you hungry? 
- I'm just sore.

56
00:02:17,521 --> 00:02:18,643
Let's go home and rest.

57
00:02:21,852 --> 00:02:23,625
Hey, wait, don't leave these.

58
00:02:23,932 --> 00:02:24,896
Store 'em for us.

59
00:02:25,023 --> 00:02:26,994
Yeah, until we hire a flatbed truck to carry 'em home for us.

60
00:02:28,064 --> 00:02:30,158
My left foot hurts. My right foot hurts. Carry me.

61
00:02:30,296 --> 00:02:31,530
- You carry me. 
- You carry me.

62
00:02:31,632 --> 00:02:32,637
- No, you carry me. 
- Come on.

63
00:03:30,805 --> 00:03:33,591
- What is taking him so long? 
- I don't know. Luke, come on!

64
00:03:35,546 --> 00:03:38,685
Oh, god, I walked right into a cobweb.

65
00:03:39,634 --> 00:03:41,424
So, what's the shape of the place?

66
00:03:41,501 --> 00:03:44,538
- It was a really big cobweb. 
- Terrible. So what's the story?

67
00:03:44,613 --> 00:03:47,047
- Is there a spider on me? 
- Suck it up, big guy, and tell us the scoop.

68
00:03:47,123 --> 00:03:49,755
- It's not so bad. 
- So it's not so good.

69
00:03:49,832 --> 00:03:51,256
Not so bad is not so good.

70
00:03:51,338 --> 00:03:54,317
- No, really, it's not bad. The floors... 
- Are rotted!

71
00:03:54,385 --> 00:03:56,160
- I knew it. They need to be replaced. 
- It's a disaster.

72
00:03:56,212 --> 00:03:58,260
The floors are fine. They need refinishing,

73
00:03:58,343 --> 00:04:00,948
but they're really nice quartersawn oak floors.

74
00:04:01,057 --> 00:04:01,809
What about the roof?

75
00:04:01,906 --> 00:04:03,067
- The roof... 
- Is shot?

76
00:04:03,155 --> 00:04:04,727
- It's caving in. 
- The walls, too?

77
00:04:04,804 --> 00:04:06,141
Along with our hopes and dreams.

78
00:04:06,196 --> 00:04:08,603
No, the roof is fine. Some shingles need replacing,

79
00:04:08,736 --> 00:04:10,614
but that looks like the extent of it.

80
00:04:10,656 --> 00:04:13,252
- Almost done here, folks. 
- Great, Kirk. You find any mold?

81
00:04:13,345 --> 00:04:15,329
You mean, did I find any silent death?

82
00:04:15,447 --> 00:04:16,549
- Not so far, no. 
- Good.

83
00:04:16,615 --> 00:04:19,754
I did tell you about the dangers of mold, right? And Ed McMahon's dog?

84
00:04:19,860 --> 00:04:20,588
Yes, you did.

85
00:04:20,706 --> 00:04:22,778
Suffered memory loss due to mold infestation.

86
00:04:23,082 --> 00:04:25,166
- Forgot how to sit. 
- Yes, it was horrible.

87
00:04:25,248 --> 00:04:27,279
It's a growth industry right now, pardon the pun.

88
00:04:27,519 --> 00:04:28,427
Mold is money.

89
00:04:28,862 --> 00:04:30,787
I just wish I wasn't so scared of finding it.

90
00:04:30,859 --> 00:04:32,686
- Well, don't look too hard then. 
- Thanks.

91
00:04:33,378 --> 00:04:36,286
So, what's the final prognosis, Luke? We're not buying a money pit, are we?

92
00:04:36,373 --> 00:04:39,395
You're gonna spend money, but it's not a pit. Might be a steal.

93
00:04:39,620 --> 00:04:40,573
It's a steal!

94
00:04:40,792 --> 00:04:42,405
We are such great businesswomen.

95
00:04:42,543 --> 00:04:44,838
Once you start work, you can probably have this place up

96
00:04:44,898 --> 00:04:46,953
and running in four or five months.

97
00:04:47,040 --> 00:04:50,501
Which will give the Independence Inn owners plenty of time to find our replacements.

98
00:04:50,599 --> 00:04:52,692
We could be running our own inn in less than a year.

99
00:04:54,004 --> 00:04:55,769
What's the matter Kirk? Mold?

100
00:04:55,907 --> 00:04:57,505
No, mouse!

101
00:04:58,897 --> 00:05:01,373
We all knew that our education at Chilton would be exemplary,

102
00:05:01,452 --> 00:05:02,840
but it was the people at Chilton.

103
00:05:02,948 --> 00:05:05,359
All my friends - Hi Marcy, love you.

104
00:05:05,528 --> 00:05:07,074
Cody and Debbie, love you, too.

105
00:05:07,224 --> 00:05:09,322
The faculty, the administrative staff.

106
00:05:09,595 --> 00:05:12,297
Even our janitorial staff - Jaime and Joachim.

107
00:05:12,432 --> 00:05:14,464
I can't count the number of times you guys made me laugh...

108
00:05:14,530 --> 00:05:16,000
- Does she need medical attention? 
- Paris.

109
00:05:16,097 --> 00:05:18,727
Jaime and Joachim aren't even getting a copy of this. She's maroon.

110
00:05:18,806 --> 00:05:20,465
It's the end of the year, people get nostalgic.

111
00:05:20,722 --> 00:05:22,642
So, how's your valedictorian speech coming along?

112
00:05:22,994 --> 00:05:26,512
Oh, it's okay. Pretty standard. Boring.

113
00:05:26,686 --> 00:05:28,365
'We love the school, blah blah blah.'

114
00:05:28,529 --> 00:05:29,969
No one listens to those things anyhow, so -

115
00:05:30,030 --> 00:05:32,481
Relax, I'm okay with you making valedictorian over me.

116
00:05:32,691 --> 00:05:34,699
Oh, good, thanks.

117
00:05:34,797 --> 00:05:35,421
Sure.

118
00:05:35,626 --> 00:05:38,744
I actually googled the personal histories of Ivy League valedictorians

119
00:05:38,811 --> 00:05:41,744
going back twenty-five years, and found some enlightening statistics.

120
00:05:41,878 --> 00:05:44,745
They don't necessarily do too well in later life, did you know that?

121
00:05:44,976 --> 00:05:46,025
- No. 
- Oh, yeah.

122
00:05:46,127 --> 00:05:49,211
A lot of business failures, crumbled marriages, suicides, obesity.

123
00:05:49,307 --> 00:05:52,070
A bunch died in car crashes, several did time,

124
00:05:52,194 --> 00:05:54,641
one suffocated when his cat fell asleep on his face.

125
00:05:54,702 --> 00:05:55,763
Okay, well, thanks again.

126
00:05:55,881 --> 00:05:58,846
Okay, A/V geek, just pan my body nice and slow.

127
00:05:59,100 --> 00:06:00,520
- Why? 
- Yeah, why?

128
00:06:00,815 --> 00:06:02,548
Because I'll never look better than I do now.

129
00:06:02,645 --> 00:06:03,961
Come on ladies, we don't have all day.

130
00:06:07,622 --> 00:06:09,705
A/V geek, I'm going to need six minutes.

131
00:06:09,782 --> 00:06:11,365
- You're only allowed two. 
- Rolling!

132
00:06:11,441 --> 00:06:12,337
Rolling.

133
00:06:12,500 --> 00:06:14,938
Fellow Chilton seniors, it's been quite a year...

134
00:06:18,287 --> 00:06:19,640
I hate this.

135
00:06:20,208 --> 00:06:23,142
One guest. In the whole inn, one guy.

136
00:06:23,234 --> 00:06:25,322
And I pulled towel duty today.

137
00:06:25,390 --> 00:06:28,113
It's especially awful handling guest towels

138
00:06:28,195 --> 00:06:30,638
when you know exactly which guests the towels belong to.

139
00:06:30,792 --> 00:06:33,278
It's his mites on those towels.

140
00:06:33,499 --> 00:06:34,759
Don't be gross.

141
00:06:34,964 --> 00:06:37,734
This is degrading for a man of my capabilities.

142
00:06:37,836 --> 00:06:39,484
Well, what about me? I've got no kitchen.

143
00:06:39,578 --> 00:06:41,555
I'm a chef. My skills are deteriorating.

144
00:06:41,759 --> 00:06:44,406
I need to saut�, emulsify, marinate.

145
00:06:44,565 --> 00:06:46,864
I need more mental stimulation.

146
00:06:46,972 --> 00:06:50,484
I need to frickin' fry a dead animal in a skillet. I'm going nuts.

147
00:06:50,590 --> 00:06:52,660
- I should've been a dancer. 
- What?

148
00:06:52,809 --> 00:06:55,362
My mother put me in dance school and I rebelled,

149
00:06:55,441 --> 00:06:58,277
I wanted to kick the football. I should not have.

150
00:06:58,343 --> 00:07:01,313
I've seen you dance and you jump around like a duck.

151
00:07:01,395 --> 00:07:03,142
You know, I'm getting mighty sick of you.

152
00:07:03,290 --> 00:07:04,713
Not as sick as I am of you.

153
00:07:04,789 --> 00:07:07,647
You know what, you do his towels. I'm not doing his towels anymore.

154
00:07:07,738 --> 00:07:09,941
I'm not doing his stupid towels. I hate that stupid guy

155
00:07:10,028 --> 00:07:11,974
with his stupid newspaper. He's stupid.

156
00:07:12,066 --> 00:07:14,017
Yo, guys, no bickering in front of the guest.

157
00:07:14,289 --> 00:07:17,591
Tell it to Deney Terrio here. I should've been a dancer.

158
00:07:17,903 --> 00:07:21,416
Lorelai, how long can we keep this up?

159
00:07:21,637 --> 00:07:22,495
Keep what up?

160
00:07:22,604 --> 00:07:24,560
We have one guest,

161
00:07:24,653 --> 00:07:26,607
half the rooms are still closed from the fire,

162
00:07:26,705 --> 00:07:30,341
most of the staff is laid off, I am doing mite towels,

163
00:07:30,443 --> 00:07:33,571
and the owner's son is walking around with a bunch of men in suits.

164
00:07:33,658 --> 00:07:35,431
Yeah, John's here. That can't be good.

165
00:07:35,610 --> 00:07:38,783
John is here looking things over for the renovation

166
00:07:38,901 --> 00:07:42,114
that will reopen all the closed rooms so we can be up and running again.

167
00:07:42,205 --> 00:07:43,065
Stop worrying.

168
00:07:43,213 --> 00:07:44,673
- Okay. 
- Okay.

169
00:07:47,536 --> 00:07:49,604
Independence Inn, Lorelai speaking.

170
00:07:49,732 --> 00:07:52,215
- Lorelai, it's your mother. 
- Mother, hi.

171
00:07:52,328 --> 00:07:55,497
I'm calling to find out how it's going to work at Rory's graduation.

172
00:07:55,652 --> 00:07:57,295
Are we going to be sitting together?

173
00:07:57,878 --> 00:08:00,782
Well, mmm... 

174
00:08:01,130 --> 00:08:03,716
- Lorelai. 
- Sorry. Hmm.

175
00:08:04,054 --> 00:08:04,786
Lorelai.

176
00:08:05,063 --> 00:08:06,820
Mom, of course we'll be sitting together. We're family.

177
00:08:06,910 --> 00:08:08,893
Well, I knew that. I just wasn't sure if you did.

178
00:08:08,999 --> 00:08:10,310
Well, we're sitting together.

179
00:08:10,531 --> 00:08:11,892
- Good. 
- Yes, it is.

180
00:08:12,052 --> 00:08:13,296
Ask her about the gift, Emily.

181
00:08:13,470 --> 00:08:15,181
- Dad? 
- He's on the other line.

182
00:08:15,462 --> 00:08:17,796
Oh, sure got the quiet thing down there.

183
00:08:17,900 --> 00:08:20,628
I'm on the upstairs portable, but I'm on my way downstairs.

184
00:08:20,710 --> 00:08:22,359
I see your mother now. Hello Emily.

185
00:08:22,528 --> 00:08:23,424
Hello Richard.

186
00:08:23,532 --> 00:08:25,729
I'm on my way to the couch and am about to sit.

187
00:08:25,918 --> 00:08:27,494
It's like the thrilling day of radio here.

188
00:08:27,618 --> 00:08:29,481
We wanted to ask you about a gift for Rory.

189
00:08:29,589 --> 00:08:31,340
It's a big gift, a little extravagant.

190
00:08:31,483 --> 00:08:33,270
But it's a big occasion, so it makes sense.

191
00:08:33,357 --> 00:08:34,444
We wanna buy her a car.

192
00:08:34,653 --> 00:08:36,640
Well, I think that's a great idea.

193
00:08:36,912 --> 00:08:38,443
- Really? 
- Wonderful.

194
00:08:38,581 --> 00:08:40,972
Yeah, Rory needs to get back and forth from Yale a lot,

195
00:08:41,069 --> 00:08:43,384
and the quicker she can do it, the more I get to see her,

196
00:08:43,455 --> 00:08:45,252
so it's really kind of a present for me, too.

197
00:08:45,602 --> 00:08:48,140
- Yes, right. 
- I suppose so.

198
00:08:48,279 --> 00:08:50,424
- Didn't think of that. 
- Just not a gas guzzler.

199
00:08:50,587 --> 00:08:54,188
- And no Ferrari's or Lamborghini's. 
